{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"31028618-6313-4746-bee1-ea84cdd48e61","content":"## CPU Baseline Instruction Set Change\n\n**.NET has been raising the minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level.** .NET 9 raised the Linux x86-64 baseline from **x86-64-v1** to **x86-64-v2** (requiring SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT). If .NET 11 further raised it to **x86-64-v3**, that adds requirements for **AVX, AVX2, FMA, BMI1, BMI2** — instructions only available starting with **Haswell (2013)**.\n\nYour 2012-era nodes are likely **Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge**, which have AVX but **lack AVX2, FMA, and BMI**. That's why they fail at startup.\n\n### Your other platforms are unaffected because:\n- **Windows Arm64** — Arm has its own baseline; not impacted by x86 changes\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Linux Arm64)** — same, Arm baseline is separate\n\n### Options:\n1. **Retire pre-2013 x86 hardware** (recommended — it's 13+ years old)\n2. **Check if a `x86-64-v2` compat build** of the runtime is available (some .NET versions offer this)\n3. **Stay on .NET 10 LTS** for those specific nodes until hardware is refreshed\n\nYou can verify a node's support by running:\n```bash\n# Check for AVX2 (key v3 instruction)\ngrep -o 'avx2' /proc/cpuinfo | head -1\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"44f33ef8-d0d6-4f19-803c-cbb19392fecb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's evolving hardware requirements, so I can answer directly.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, let me think more carefully...\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The .NET 9 change was about the x86-64 baseline. Let me think about what .NET 10 and .NET 11 would do.\n\n\nSo .NET 9 made this shift for Linux x86-64 specifically, requiring the v2 instruction set at the runtime level. The user is experiencing this when moving to .NET 11, which would continue or potentially extend these requirements. This is a real compatibility issue for older hardware that predates these instruction sets. AVX2 wasn't introduced until Haswell in 2013, so 2012 hardware would fail if .NET 11 bumped the baseline to x86-64-v3.\n\nBut I should focus on what's actually documented versus what I'm speculating about. .NET 9 definitely introduced the x86-64-v2 requirement, and the error message the user is seeing matches the exact runtime error when CPU baseline requirements aren't met. The most straightforward explanation is that .NET raised the instruction set baseline again between versions 10 and 11.\n\nIf .NET 11 moved to x86-64-v3, that would require AVX2, FMA, BMI1, and BMI2—features that Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge CPUs from 2012 don't have. They support AVX and SSE4.2, but not the v3 extensions, which would explain why the hardware suddenly fails after the upgrade. I'm not entirely certain about .NET 11's exact CPU baseline requirements since it hasn't shipped yet, but the underlying mechanism is solid—each .NET release has progressively raised the x86-64 baseline, and if .NET 11 does move to x86-64-v3, older processors simply won't support the required instruction sets.","outputTokens":1783,"requestId":"E03C:2F6FBA:7795AF9:8444924:69F4065D"},"id":"d4f60e6a-5f61-41c3-924f-55e04ae30808","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:48:49.947Z","parentId":"0b0703e3-b691-40e4-ae86-f96f48d44952"}
